05634nam a22008415i 9780231547369DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018008523  a97802315473697 a10.7312/evan187582doi  a(DE-B1597)514668  a(OCoLC)1057665600  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBH301.P64bE93 2018 4aBH301.P64b.E936 2019 7aPHI0010002bisacsh04a320.109222231 aEvans, Fred, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPublic Art and the Fragility of Democracy :bAn Essay in Political Aesthetics /cFred Evans. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b22 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Themes in Philosophy, Social Criticism, and the Arts00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE AND ACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. DEMOCRACY’S FRAGILITY AND THE POLITICAL AESTHETICS OF PUBLIC ART -- t2. VOICES AND PLACES: THE SPACE OF PUBLIC ART AND WODICZKO’S THE HOMELESS PROJECTION -- t3. DEMOCRACY’S “EMPTY PLACE”: RAWLS’S POLITICAL LIBERALISM AND DERRIDA’S DEMOCRACY TO COME -- t4. PUBLIC ART’S “PLAIN TABLET”: THE POLITICAL AESTHETICS OF CONTEMPORARY ART -- t5. DEMOCRACY AND PUBLIC ART: BADIOU AND RANCIÈRE -- t6. THE POLITICAL AESTHETICS OF CHICAGO’S MILLENNIUM PARK -- t7. THE POLITICAL AESTHETICS OF NEW YORK’S NATIONAL 9/11 MEMORIAL -- t8. PUBLIC ART AS AN ACT OF CITIZENSHIP -- tAppendix: Badiou on “Being and the Void” -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPublic space is political space. When a work of public art is put up or taken down, it is an inherently political statement, and the work’s aesthetics are inextricably entwined with its political valences. Democracy’s openness allows public art to explore its values critically and to suggest new ones. However, it also facilitates artworks that can surreptitiously or fortuitously undermine democratic values. Today, as bigotry and authoritarianism are on the rise and democratic movements seek to combat them, as Confederate monuments fall and sculptures celebrating diversity rise, the struggle over the values enshrined in the public arena has taken on a new urgency.In this book, Fred Evans develops philosophical and political criteria for assessing how public art can respond to the fragility of democracy. He calls for considering such artworks as acts of citizenship, pointing to their capacity to resist autocratic tendencies and reveal new dimensions of democratic society. Through close considerations of Chicago’s Millennium Park and New York’s National September 11 Memorial, Evans shows how a wide range of artworks participate in democratic dialogues. A nuanced consideration of contemporary art, aesthetics, and political theory, this book is a timely and rigorous elucidation of how thoughtful public art can contribute to the flourishing of a democratic way of life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAestheticsxPolitical aspects. 0aDemocracy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066255908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Package 2018z978311065486808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018 Englishz978311060421408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018